         <entryFree xml:id="fāng" type="architectural-feature">
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-1" xml:lang="en" type="preferred" source="biblk000116-1">squared beams (preferred)</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">方</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">方</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">fāng</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-5" xml:lang="Wade-Giles">fang</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-6" xml:lang="en" type="literal_translation">square; square-shaped (beam or joist) (lit.)</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-7" xml:lang="en" source="biblk000116-2">lintel</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-8" xml:lang="en" source="biblk000116-3">rafter plate; a horizontal structural member under and parallel to the purlins</term>
            <note type="Note (brief)">
               <p xml:lang="en">As an architectural member in the Yingzao fashi (1103), the fang 方 refers to a timber whose cross-section measurement utilizes the dancai for the building as a standard. Its use is relatively flexible, and the term is often modified by the names of the different location where it is used within the building. <s source="biblk000116-4">In the Qing dynasty fang 枋 is used rather than 方.</s></p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">宋營造法式中， 方則指 斷面尺寸一單材為基準的小斷面構建，使用較靈活， 一所處位置有不同的名稱。</p>  
            </note>
